				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\Delta {G}^{0}=\Delta {H}^{0}-T\cdot \Delta {S}^{0}$$\end{document}

Alkaline fuel cells and electrolyzers in the classic design are generally based on an aqueous solution of potassium hydroxide (KOH). Here, the hydroxide ions (OH−) are responsible for the electrochemical current in-between the electrodes. In fuel cell mode (gas consumption) hydroxide ions are produced at the oxygen electrode and consumed at the hydrogen electrode. In electrolysis mode (gas production) the flow direction is reverse. The electrochemical equations are given below; they are reversible in general:hydrogenelectrode:H2+2OH-↔2H2O+2e--0.828V\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
